\begin_layout Standard
vi) 
\emph on
It is not quite clear from the presentation if the authors consider the
 oscillations to be isothermal or not.
 Although the T curve is flat, this is the macroscopic temperature.
 What is the actual surface/nanoparticle temperature (I know this is a difficult
 Q but the authors should try to address it a little deeper).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A very valid point made by the referee.
 We are ourselves are very much in doubt whether the reaction is isothermal
 or not on a microscopic level.
 On one hand the free energy pr.
 reaction is quite large and possibly distributed on a rather small amount
 of nanoparticles.
 On the other hand heat transport in a small volume at 1
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

bar should be very efficient.
 As mentioned in the paper, we have done several attempts at observing a
 possible sign for local temperature effects but so far without results.
 Thus one so far has to conclude that the experimental results points towards
 constant temperature also at the microscopic level but we are not confident
 enough in this yet to draw solid conclusions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The manuscript has been revised to make this point more clear by adding
 the following sentence to the discussion:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

which would point towards a constant temperature even on the microscopic
 scale.
 However, the experimental data are so far not good enough to make final
 conclusions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
vii) 
\emph on
Knowing the flow rate through the reactor and the gas composition at the
 inlet and outlet (by MS) it should be possible to estimate how much the
 O2/CO2 ratio varies along the flow reaction for the high rate and low rate
 regimes of the oscillatory reaction, which in turn will be valuble information
 for identifying the mechanism.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In principle such a calculation could be carried out, however, in practice
 it is quite difficult.
 The diffusion length of the gas molecules is larger than the size of the
 reactor diameter and thus the details of the gradients becomes quite complex
 in the case of non-full conversion.
 In the case of full conversion, the gradient might be more straight-forward
 but here we lack detailed knowledge about the the actual conversion rate
 of the individual particles.
 As mentioned in the paper, a very small fraction of the particles might
 be able to convert all reactants in which case the gradient will be very
 steep for the first few micrometers.
 In the case of low conversion pr.
 particle a more constant gradient along the reactor will be expected.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
viii) 
\emph on
Finally one very important point: In order to observe oscillations in the
 reactant and reaction product concentrations (as the authors do) for a
 large number supported particles, they need to be reasonably synchronized.
 The authors should discuss the origin of synchronization.
 At high pressures the common "synchronizer" are either or both of gas phase
 gradients in concentrations or the temperature variations.
 If one excludes them and propose a pure surface effect it is more tricky
 to find the mechanism.
 One such mechanism is spill over (see Ref 12 for a brief discussion but
 there are a few more papers).
 This should be discussed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We believe that even though we suggest a surface effect as the responsible
 mechanism for the oscillations the gas phase can still act as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

synchronizer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because the changing gas-composition will collectively either oxidize or
 reduce the particles through the oscillation cycle.
 Also, it should be noticed that for a given sample the temperature window
 which shows oscillations is rather small indicating that the synchronization
 is not very robust but depends on rather careful parameter tuning.
\end_layout

